00:01:27.690 --> 00:01:29.933
But for now, you
just have to watch

00:01:29.933 --> 00:01:31.350
and participate
in the discussion,

00:01:31.350 --> 00:01:33.350
and see what happens.

00:01:33.350 --> 00:01:35.400
So [? Kalpesh ?]
asked the following,

00:01:35.400 --> 00:01:39.330
when I started,
actually, the class, I

00:01:39.330 --> 00:01:45.030
claimed that optical rays have
to satisfy Fermat's principle.

00:01:45.030 --> 00:01:49.590
So therefore, they must always
go where their path is minimal.

00:01:49.590 --> 00:01:54.670
So in the case of a GRIN,
I use the notation here

00:01:54.670 --> 00:01:59.320
where the gray area in
the slide corresponds

00:01:59.320 --> 00:02:01.590
to high index of refraction.

00:02:01.590 --> 00:02:04.650
The sort of whitest
area is low in index.

00:02:04.650 --> 00:02:06.490
So this is like a typical GRIN.

00:02:06.490 --> 00:02:09.520
You can imagine this profile
may be quadratic or something

00:02:09.520 --> 00:02:11.380
like that.

00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:15.460
And what we said in
the class, and you all

00:02:15.460 --> 00:02:17.770
believed me except for
[? Kalpesh, ?] I guess.

00:02:17.770 --> 00:02:21.040
What I said in the class is that
if you have a ray that enters

00:02:21.040 --> 00:02:25.740
this medium sort of off
axis, like shown here,

00:02:25.740 --> 00:02:27.730
the ray will actually
bend inwards.

00:02:27.730 --> 00:02:33.240
So all of the rays will come to
a focus somewhere around there.

00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:38.200
But [? Kalpesh ?] asked,
why doesn't it do this?

00:02:38.200 --> 00:02:40.488
I mean, the rays here
seems to actually--

00:02:40.488 --> 00:02:42.280
it seems to do the
wrong thing, doesn't it?

00:02:42.280 --> 00:02:46.020
It seems to go towards
the high-index area,

00:02:46.020 --> 00:02:48.150
whereas the minimum
path principle

00:02:48.150 --> 00:02:51.440
would suggest that the ray
should go outwards like this,

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:53.040
towards the low-index area.

00:02:53.040 --> 00:02:54.860
So the question is,
what will the ray do?

00:02:54.860 --> 00:02:57.270
Will it do this or that?

00:02:57.270 --> 00:02:58.680
We know from experience--

00:02:58.680 --> 00:03:02.760
I mean, we know from experience,
from experiment, I should say--

00:03:02.760 --> 00:03:04.320
that gain optics do focus.

00:03:04.320 --> 00:03:07.470
So we know that physics
actually behaves like this.

00:03:07.470 --> 00:03:10.200
But the question is, how is that
consistent with our description

00:03:10.200 --> 00:03:11.260
of the physical system?

00:03:11.260 --> 00:03:12.177
What is going on here?

00:03:14.980 --> 00:03:16.480
So that is
[? Kalpesh's ?] question.

00:03:16.480 --> 00:03:21.790
And what I said when he asked
it in class, more or less--

00:03:21.790 --> 00:03:23.740
I cannot remember
exactly what I said--

00:03:23.740 --> 00:03:27.400
but I said to properly
contemplate the answer,

00:03:27.400 --> 00:03:30.372
we must consider
not just this ray.

00:03:30.372 --> 00:03:32.080
If we just have this
ray, we don't really

00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:34.000
know whether the ray will go.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.860
But we also have another
ray, the one that is on axis.

00:03:38.860 --> 00:03:40.510
Now these two
rays, they actually

00:03:40.510 --> 00:03:42.700
originated at the same point.

00:03:42.700 --> 00:03:44.020
Where did they originate?

00:03:44.020 --> 00:03:47.870
At infinity, somewhere far
out to the left over here.

00:03:47.870 --> 00:03:52.930
And what I said is that
basically these rays,

00:03:52.930 --> 00:03:57.760
because this ray goes through
a longer optical path,

00:03:57.760 --> 00:04:04.060
because it is entered
in a high-index medium,

00:04:04.060 --> 00:04:07.840
this has too much,
its optical path.

00:04:07.840 --> 00:04:11.320
So this ray actually
enters a lower index.

00:04:11.320 --> 00:04:14.380
So therefore, it starts
with a sort of predicament

00:04:14.380 --> 00:04:17.410
that points to a
smaller optical path.

00:04:17.410 --> 00:04:18.970
So in order to
catch up, in order

00:04:18.970 --> 00:04:23.380
to match the longer
optical path of this ray,

00:04:23.380 --> 00:04:28.270
this ray, the sort
of off-axis ray,

00:04:28.270 --> 00:04:30.880
must follow along at
a geometrical distance

00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:35.770
so that the longer geometrical
distance times the lower index

00:04:35.770 --> 00:04:38.426
kind of will balance,
will compensate.

00:04:40.990 --> 00:04:43.720
So this is where we left it.

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:51.510
But then [? Kalpesh ?] came
back to me at the quiz,

00:04:51.510 --> 00:04:56.410
and he told me, I
don't believe it.

00:04:56.410 --> 00:04:58.512
You want to rephrase
your question?

00:04:58.512 --> 00:04:59.680
AUDIENCE: No, [INAUDIBLE].

00:04:59.680 --> 00:05:02.180
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: OK, so I
presented your objection well.

00:05:04.790 --> 00:05:09.170
So first of all, does anybody
else from here or from Boston

00:05:09.170 --> 00:05:11.610
have some additional
insight about this?

00:05:11.610 --> 00:05:13.220
I can go back to the original.

00:05:13.220 --> 00:05:15.230
We'll call it the
[? "Kalpesh ?] Question."

00:05:15.230 --> 00:05:16.390
Yes.

00:05:16.390 --> 00:05:28.170
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:05:28.170 --> 00:05:30.728
AUDIENCE: We didn't
hear the question.

00:05:30.728 --> 00:05:32.520
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Is your button pushed?

00:05:32.520 --> 00:05:33.020
Yes.

00:05:33.020 --> 00:05:35.400
You have to make sure
that the red light is on.

00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:36.330
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:05:36.330 --> 00:05:39.940
Yeah, in the standard
case of an interface,

00:05:39.940 --> 00:05:43.450
we have a ray propagating
from left to right

00:05:43.450 --> 00:05:46.810
and we have an interface,
which is top to bottom.

00:05:46.810 --> 00:05:48.970
But in this case,
the interface could

00:05:48.970 --> 00:05:52.390
be considered to be left
to right, couldn't we?

00:05:52.390 --> 00:05:56.990
Because the refractive index
change is from top to bottom.

00:05:56.990 --> 00:05:59.020
So the interface--

00:05:59.020 --> 00:06:02.170
I'm just thinking that if we
consider the interface to be

00:06:02.170 --> 00:06:04.060
from left to right,
then the normal

00:06:04.060 --> 00:06:05.680
will be from top to bottom.

00:06:05.680 --> 00:06:09.567
And still, the Snell's law will
lead us to the correct answer,

00:06:09.567 --> 00:06:10.400
correct [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:10.400 --> 00:06:11.442
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yes.

00:06:11.442 --> 00:06:14.270
You can actually--
by the time you

00:06:14.270 --> 00:06:17.510
reach here whether the
ray has already been,

00:06:17.510 --> 00:06:18.690
you can make that argument.

00:06:18.690 --> 00:06:20.320
Because now the ray is really--

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:21.445
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:06:21.445 --> 00:06:22.070
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:06:22.070 --> 00:06:22.640
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
But the question

00:06:22.640 --> 00:06:25.580
is, why should the ray start
bending inwards to begin with?

00:06:25.580 --> 00:06:27.410
Why should it not bend this way?

00:06:27.410 --> 00:06:28.220
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:06:28.220 --> 00:06:29.520
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: And if
it starts bending this way,

00:06:29.520 --> 00:06:32.160
then Snell's law also said
that it should go like this.

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:35.270
So there's something amiss here.

00:06:35.270 --> 00:06:36.030
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:06:36.030 --> 00:06:37.030
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: OK.

00:06:41.183 --> 00:06:42.850
So there's no doubt--
as I said, there's

00:06:42.850 --> 00:06:45.580
no doubt that the correct
physics is this one.

00:06:45.580 --> 00:06:48.520
The question is, is
our model correct?

00:06:48.520 --> 00:06:51.760
Is our claim, all this stuff we
developed about optical paths

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:54.640
and so on, does it really
agree with the physics?

00:06:58.430 --> 00:07:03.530
So I don't hear any-- any
other comments or objections

00:07:03.530 --> 00:07:04.060
about this?

00:07:04.060 --> 00:07:13.280
Or-- so let's go with
a little bit more care

00:07:13.280 --> 00:07:16.190
through this argument.

00:07:16.190 --> 00:07:17.820
What is happening.

00:07:17.820 --> 00:07:20.210
Let's take out the medium,
so there's nothing now,

00:07:20.210 --> 00:07:21.840
just free space.

00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:24.770
So the rays started at infinity.

00:07:24.770 --> 00:07:27.380
They're heading
towards infinity.

00:07:27.380 --> 00:07:31.710
Everybody's happy with a
straight path, because clearly,

00:07:31.710 --> 00:07:34.370
the straight line
in uniform space

00:07:34.370 --> 00:07:37.700
is the shortest
between two points.

00:07:37.700 --> 00:07:40.130
And clearly, these two rays--

00:07:40.130 --> 00:07:43.830
they never really meet, but
we say they meet at infinity

00:07:43.830 --> 00:07:47.510
at the left and they also meet
again at infinity to the right.

00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:52.430
And they will have traversed the
same optical path by the same--

00:07:52.430 --> 00:07:54.470
by the time they meet
again at infinity.

00:07:54.470 --> 00:07:58.640
Now, you might ask, well,
what does it really mean?

00:07:58.640 --> 00:08:00.680
I mean, after all, the
path itself is infinite.

00:08:00.680 --> 00:08:03.890
What does it mean they
travel equal infinite paths?

00:08:03.890 --> 00:08:06.260
Well, I can get, actually,
around this problem

00:08:06.260 --> 00:08:10.550
pretty easily because I can
actually put some boundaries

00:08:10.550 --> 00:08:11.870
to the left and to the right.

00:08:11.870 --> 00:08:15.170
And I can keep these boundaries
at a finite distance.

00:08:15.170 --> 00:08:18.210
Then you can definitely
measure the optical path.

00:08:18.210 --> 00:08:20.240
Then you can start
moving the boundaries

00:08:20.240 --> 00:08:23.990
farther away to the left and
farther away to the right.

00:08:23.990 --> 00:08:27.500
The optical paths remain the
same as I move the boundaries.

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:30.570
And I can continue this
process until the boundaries

00:08:30.570 --> 00:08:32.360
are really, really very far.

00:08:32.360 --> 00:08:35.900
This is mathematically really
what we mean by "infinity."

00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:37.789
So I can get around
this difficulty.

00:08:37.789 --> 00:08:41.510
I can certainly talk
about equal paths,

00:08:41.510 --> 00:08:45.590
even if the paths are
actually infinite.

00:08:45.590 --> 00:08:47.810
This is sort of a
technicality, but nevertheless

00:08:47.810 --> 00:08:53.870
an important one so we know
that we're on solid ground.

00:08:53.870 --> 00:08:56.075
So I hope I have
convinced you that Fermat

00:08:56.075 --> 00:08:59.420
is happy in this
case of free space,

00:08:59.420 --> 00:09:02.450
because the rays
indeed propagate

00:09:02.450 --> 00:09:05.000
through the minimum
path, and indeed, they're

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:06.740
all equal in terms of path.

00:09:12.710 --> 00:09:15.980
Now, this is really
not anything new.

00:09:15.980 --> 00:09:18.120
This is what I said before.

00:09:18.120 --> 00:09:23.420
And basically, this says
that the longer geometrical

00:09:23.420 --> 00:09:28.550
path actually gets to be
multiplied by a lower index,

00:09:28.550 --> 00:09:33.980
so therefore, by the time
the rays meet again here,

00:09:33.980 --> 00:09:36.710
they still have
equal optical paths.

00:09:36.710 --> 00:09:39.980
Because the path to the left
is equal-- they both came

00:09:39.980 --> 00:09:43.040
from infinity-- then the
two trajectories here,

00:09:43.040 --> 00:09:45.710
if you sort integrate the
optical path all along,

00:09:45.710 --> 00:09:47.060
you would get equal answer.

00:09:52.597 --> 00:09:53.180
Are you happy?

00:09:57.270 --> 00:09:59.714
Maybe push the button in.

00:09:59.714 --> 00:10:06.740
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
Instead of a wave coming

00:10:06.740 --> 00:10:09.590
towards a whole cross-section
of the GRIN lens,

00:10:09.590 --> 00:10:13.940
suppose if you have a small spot
coming only towards the top.

00:10:13.940 --> 00:10:17.950
So will it go towards
up in that case?

00:10:17.950 --> 00:10:19.450
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
So the question

00:10:19.450 --> 00:10:21.370
is, suppose I take out this ray.

00:10:21.370 --> 00:10:25.800
Will the ray-- will
this thing also focus?

00:10:25.800 --> 00:10:26.550
What do you think?

00:10:34.390 --> 00:10:38.210
AUDIENCE: I think we have only
a single ray towards the top,

00:10:38.210 --> 00:10:42.200
which is coming towards
the lower refractive index,

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:44.980
then it should go towards
the lower refractive index

00:10:44.980 --> 00:10:50.680
because it doesn't need to
match with the same phase

00:10:50.680 --> 00:10:53.960
as the center wave.

00:10:53.960 --> 00:10:57.700
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
OK, let's not quite

00:10:57.700 --> 00:11:00.040
argue about a single
ray, because there's

00:11:00.040 --> 00:11:02.170
no such thing as a single ray.

00:11:02.170 --> 00:11:07.630
If you illuminate a very, real
infinitesimal optical spot

00:11:07.630 --> 00:11:11.260
over here, as we will learn in
wave optics, what you will get

00:11:11.260 --> 00:11:17.020
is not a sort of
straight line of light,

00:11:17.020 --> 00:11:18.860
but you will get a very
strong diffraction.

00:11:18.860 --> 00:11:21.610
So what will happen if you
illuminate a single spot here

00:11:21.610 --> 00:11:24.310
is the light will spread
violently into the GRIN.

00:11:24.310 --> 00:11:27.400
And then what will happen is
a kind of a complicated issue.

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:34.870
So the way, essentially
by claiming the fraction,

00:11:34.870 --> 00:11:36.700
I got around the
problem that you're

00:11:36.700 --> 00:11:40.870
posing, because as long as I
have a finite pencil of rays

00:11:40.870 --> 00:11:43.780
coming in here, then the
same thing will happen,

00:11:43.780 --> 00:11:47.620
because I can always
compare two rays that enter

00:11:47.620 --> 00:11:49.090
at slightly different indices.

00:11:49.090 --> 00:11:50.770
Then the same argument follows.

00:11:50.770 --> 00:11:55.130
So this pencil will also
kind of focus in the same--

00:11:55.130 --> 00:12:01.510
so basically, I can remove
parts of that ray diagram

00:12:01.510 --> 00:12:03.970
and the same thing will
still happen according

00:12:03.970 --> 00:12:05.130
to geometrical optics.

00:12:05.130 --> 00:12:07.180
Diffraction says
differently, but according

00:12:07.180 --> 00:12:10.930
to geometrical optics, I can
remove portions of these rays

00:12:10.930 --> 00:12:15.362
and still have focusing.

00:12:15.362 --> 00:12:17.620
There's another objection
that I haven't had yet.

00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:23.890
I'm not finished.

00:12:23.890 --> 00:12:26.000
I am not satisfied
that I answered

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:27.572
[? Kalpesh's ?] question yet.

00:12:27.572 --> 00:12:29.530
And I see that [? Kalpesh ?]
is also skeptical,

00:12:29.530 --> 00:12:31.570
and I hope someone--

00:12:31.570 --> 00:12:33.850
I have another slide to
bring up the objection,

00:12:33.850 --> 00:12:38.190
but I'm wondering if
someone will bring it up,

00:12:38.190 --> 00:12:39.320
or maybe another objection.

00:12:39.320 --> 00:12:41.940
At least there's one
objection that I thought of,

00:12:41.940 --> 00:12:43.140
but there may be others.

00:12:47.460 --> 00:12:49.000
AUDIENCE: Question.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:50.390
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yeah.

00:12:50.390 --> 00:12:54.260
AUDIENCE: Why is it that
the ray on top bends

00:12:54.260 --> 00:12:57.260
to slow down to
meet the ray that's

00:12:57.260 --> 00:13:00.050
traveling through the denser
medium versus both of them

00:13:00.050 --> 00:13:03.188
traveling to the less
dense optical medium,

00:13:03.188 --> 00:13:04.230
because that could also--

00:13:04.230 --> 00:13:04.820
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:13:04.820 --> 00:13:06.570
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's the objection.

00:13:06.570 --> 00:13:08.420
That's exactly the objection.

00:13:08.420 --> 00:13:13.160
So the objection is who says
that the central ray should

00:13:13.160 --> 00:13:15.530
go straight?

00:13:15.530 --> 00:13:20.150
I sort of silently
took it for granted

00:13:20.150 --> 00:13:23.050
that the central ray
here goes straight,

00:13:23.050 --> 00:13:25.010
and therefore,
this other ray has

00:13:25.010 --> 00:13:27.620
to race in order to meet it.

00:13:27.620 --> 00:13:29.970
Why don't the two
rays go like this?

00:13:29.970 --> 00:13:31.730
Is this your question?

00:13:31.730 --> 00:13:33.170
I mean, yes.

00:13:33.170 --> 00:13:36.493
Why don't the two rays-- why
don't they both do like this?

00:13:36.493 --> 00:13:38.160
They seem to be doing
the correct thing.

00:13:38.160 --> 00:13:42.735
They seem to be both going
toward the lower index.

00:13:46.350 --> 00:13:50.430
We know again-- we can argue
that this would happen,

00:13:50.430 --> 00:13:53.440
but we know from physics
that this does not happen.

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:58.790
So what is the physical--

00:13:58.790 --> 00:14:03.400
AUDIENCE: That can't
possibly happen by symmetry.

00:14:03.400 --> 00:14:06.160
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
OK, thank you.

00:14:06.160 --> 00:14:08.500
Accurately, it is not
a question of symmetry

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:11.800
because indeed, in
this case, I assume

00:14:11.800 --> 00:14:15.760
that the refractive
index is symmetric.

00:14:15.760 --> 00:14:19.870
However, now let me see if I
can do this without revealing

00:14:19.870 --> 00:14:20.830
my next slide.

00:14:27.910 --> 00:14:31.750
However, I can make an
asymmetric index profile.

00:14:31.750 --> 00:14:34.390
So this is a
simulation of the GRIN

00:14:34.390 --> 00:14:36.840
with a symmetric
quadratic index.

00:14:36.840 --> 00:14:39.850
Here, I made the
profile asymmetric.

00:14:39.850 --> 00:14:43.540
So basically, this
is the equation here.

00:14:43.540 --> 00:14:48.430
I should simply draw it,
except I don't have a marker.

00:14:51.020 --> 00:14:54.410
Anyway, basically here,
the index of refraction

00:14:54.410 --> 00:14:57.290
is a parabola that
has a different slope

00:14:57.290 --> 00:15:00.590
above and different slope below.

00:15:00.590 --> 00:15:04.190
So you see that even though
this is asymmetric, stubbornly,

00:15:04.190 --> 00:15:07.400
the central ray
still goes straight.

00:15:07.400 --> 00:15:10.130
Therefore, it is not
symmetry which makes

00:15:10.130 --> 00:15:12.011
the previous case impossible.

00:15:18.610 --> 00:15:22.150
AUDIENCE: But, well, I said
"symmetry," but if you go

00:15:22.150 --> 00:15:27.310
to your next one, that
ray that's going straight

00:15:27.310 --> 00:15:30.630
along the center--

00:15:30.630 --> 00:15:31.130
is it gone?

00:15:31.130 --> 00:15:34.948
Yeah, that ray goes
straight, doesn't it?

00:15:34.948 --> 00:15:35.990
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yep.

00:15:35.990 --> 00:15:37.640
AUDIENCE: And that's
because there's

00:15:37.640 --> 00:15:43.900
no transverse gradient in
the refractive index where

00:15:43.900 --> 00:15:46.210
it's propagating, I guess.

00:15:46.210 --> 00:15:47.628
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: OK, yes.

00:15:47.628 --> 00:15:48.170
That is true.

00:15:48.170 --> 00:15:50.360
There's no movement to push it.

00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:52.580
Yeah, and that, I agree with.

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:55.880
However, that really still
does not answer his question,

00:15:55.880 --> 00:16:01.165
because the reason
momentum works,

00:16:01.165 --> 00:16:03.040
the reason we apply
Snell's Law, for example,

00:16:03.040 --> 00:16:07.030
is because we claim
path minimization.

00:16:07.030 --> 00:16:09.670
So I suppose you
could argue this way.

00:16:09.670 --> 00:16:11.110
I have another
argument, actually,

00:16:11.110 --> 00:16:15.073
why this ray must go straight.

00:16:15.073 --> 00:16:16.990
Actually, I don't know
if it must go straight,

00:16:16.990 --> 00:16:23.290
but then another argument why
basically this is impossible,

00:16:23.290 --> 00:16:25.065
why this is
physically incorrect.

00:16:32.830 --> 00:16:37.260
AUDIENCE: If you do that, isn't
it true that the bottom ray's

00:16:37.260 --> 00:16:40.860
path is still longer than
the top ray's path because

00:16:40.860 --> 00:16:45.750
of the index of refraction is
low, and then it's just low

00:16:45.750 --> 00:16:47.290
all the way, and--

00:16:47.290 --> 00:16:48.542
yeah.

00:16:48.542 --> 00:16:49.750
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Exactly.

00:16:49.750 --> 00:16:57.190
If you do that,
there is no way ever

00:16:57.190 --> 00:17:00.550
that this ray will catch up.

00:17:00.550 --> 00:17:03.910
Because this ray
now, not only is it

00:17:03.910 --> 00:17:07.060
going through a higher
index of refraction,

00:17:07.060 --> 00:17:11.619
it is also following a longer
geometrical trajectory.

00:17:11.619 --> 00:17:15.970
So therefore, if these
two rays ever meet again--

00:17:15.970 --> 00:17:17.555
they might meet at
a finite distance.

00:17:17.555 --> 00:17:19.180
The way I drew them
here, at some point

00:17:19.180 --> 00:17:22.690
they will meet again, or
they might meet at infinity.

00:17:22.690 --> 00:17:25.599
They might somehow become
parallel and meet again

00:17:25.599 --> 00:17:26.530
at infinity.

00:17:26.530 --> 00:17:29.410
But no matter what,
this ray over here

00:17:29.410 --> 00:17:32.650
has traveled the
longer optical path.

00:17:32.650 --> 00:17:35.680
And now that is a clear
violation of Fermat.

00:17:35.680 --> 00:17:38.740
So we basically arrived
at an impossibility.

00:17:38.740 --> 00:17:42.190
So this is physically,
then, incorrect.

00:17:42.190 --> 00:17:50.790
That is the reason why the
rays have to bend inwards.

00:17:50.790 --> 00:17:55.080
And so the proper interpretation
of Fermat's principle--

00:17:55.080 --> 00:17:57.270
and actually, the book has
an interesting discussion

00:17:57.270 --> 00:17:59.300
about this--

00:17:59.300 --> 00:18:04.260
we can claim, yes, that Fermat
minimizes the optical path,

00:18:04.260 --> 00:18:08.520
but perhaps, at least
linguistically a more precise

00:18:08.520 --> 00:18:13.110
definition is that
Fermat requires

00:18:13.110 --> 00:18:17.520
that the path of the
rays is stationary.

00:18:17.520 --> 00:18:20.190
Now, "stationary"
in mathematics--

00:18:20.190 --> 00:18:24.480
what it means is that if
you perturb it in some way,

00:18:24.480 --> 00:18:27.030
you will get a bigger answer--

00:18:27.030 --> 00:18:28.800
if you perturb it in anyway.

00:18:28.800 --> 00:18:31.485
So remember-- I wish
I had the marker.

00:18:34.120 --> 00:18:35.823
I think I can just
use a pen, though.

00:18:39.960 --> 00:18:42.570
Let's try with a pen, and
you guys tell me in Boston

00:18:42.570 --> 00:18:43.410
if you can see it.

00:18:43.410 --> 00:18:47.670
Remember with Fermat,
we did this analogy.

00:18:47.670 --> 00:18:51.090
We said-- you can
see it, right--

00:18:51.090 --> 00:18:56.440
we said-- I'm
sorry, I should have

00:18:56.440 --> 00:18:59.220
said remember with Snell's Law.

00:18:59.220 --> 00:19:04.470
Snell's Law says that
the ray must do something

00:19:04.470 --> 00:19:10.670
like this in order to connect
this point to this point.

00:19:10.670 --> 00:19:14.480
So mathematically,
what we derive

00:19:14.480 --> 00:19:17.300
is that any other possibility--

00:19:17.300 --> 00:19:27.640
this, this, this, this,
and also, why not this?

00:19:27.640 --> 00:19:31.510
These are all different
possible ray trajectories.

00:19:31.510 --> 00:19:32.930
There's a mathematical tool.

00:19:32.930 --> 00:19:34.590
It's called "calculus
of variation,"

00:19:34.590 --> 00:19:36.550
which does a miraculous thing.

00:19:36.550 --> 00:19:40.570
It somehow compares all of
these possible trajectories,

00:19:40.570 --> 00:19:42.920
and then it arrives at
the minimum trajectory.

00:19:42.920 --> 00:19:44.830
And it tells us, no, no.

00:19:44.830 --> 00:19:47.010
No matter what-- these are
infinite possibilities.

00:19:47.010 --> 00:19:48.190
That you can imagine.

00:19:48.190 --> 00:19:50.530
But this tool,
calculus of variations,

00:19:50.530 --> 00:19:54.490
actually tells us
eventually that all of these

00:19:54.490 --> 00:19:57.220
give us a longer
total optical path.

00:19:57.220 --> 00:20:01.120
And the only true one, if you
wish, the one that minimizes,

00:20:01.120 --> 00:20:04.600
the stationary one, is the
one that I drew kind of bolder

00:20:04.600 --> 00:20:06.910
here.

00:20:06.910 --> 00:20:09.160
So this is the proper
way to interpret Fermat.

00:20:09.160 --> 00:20:14.560
It is not that a single
ray will actually

00:20:14.560 --> 00:20:17.410
look for the lower
index of refraction.

00:20:17.410 --> 00:20:18.940
It is actually
that when you have

00:20:18.940 --> 00:20:22.270
a bundle of rays that
share a common beginning

00:20:22.270 --> 00:20:26.140
and a common end,
then the trajectory

00:20:26.140 --> 00:20:30.700
that these rays will follow will
be such that they're all equal,

00:20:30.700 --> 00:20:33.850
and that this trajectory now
is stationary, in the sense

00:20:33.850 --> 00:20:36.620
that if you were to
perturb it in any way--

00:20:36.620 --> 00:20:39.070
if you were to move some
of these rays up, or down,

00:20:39.070 --> 00:20:41.020
or bend them, or
whatever-- you would end up

00:20:41.020 --> 00:20:45.220
getting a longer trajectory.

00:20:45.220 --> 00:20:47.860
That's the proper
interpretation of Fermat.

00:20:47.860 --> 00:20:52.120
So this is actually a
very interesting topic.

00:20:52.120 --> 00:20:55.100
And I confess that
when I was a student,

00:20:55.100 --> 00:20:56.290
I was also bothered by this.

00:20:56.290 --> 00:20:59.190
I mean, the rays seems to
be doing the wrong thing,

00:20:59.190 --> 00:20:59.960
after all.

00:20:59.960 --> 00:21:03.070
It seems to be going really
the way it shouldn't go.

00:21:03.070 --> 00:21:03.700
Why?

00:21:03.700 --> 00:21:07.000
The reason is as we just
described-- because the path

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:10.170
has to be stationary.

00:21:10.170 --> 00:21:12.170
The bottom line out of
this, which will actually

00:21:12.170 --> 00:21:15.730
be useful in our
ensuing discussion

00:21:15.730 --> 00:21:20.080
of Hamiltonian optics, is
that the index of refraction

00:21:20.080 --> 00:21:23.713
is acting a little
bit like gravity.

00:21:23.713 --> 00:21:25.130
Actually, it's
acting like gravity

00:21:25.130 --> 00:21:26.480
more than you would think.

00:21:26.480 --> 00:21:32.150
The index of refraction seems
to be attracting the rays, which

00:21:32.150 --> 00:21:34.850
is, again, a little bit
counterintuitive if you

00:21:34.850 --> 00:21:37.210
interpret Fermat
as a minimum path.

00:21:37.210 --> 00:21:48.590
But after we went through this
explanation, it makes sense.

00:21:48.590 --> 00:21:54.790
The index of refraction pretty
much collects rays near it.

00:21:54.790 --> 00:21:55.892
Yes, there's a question.

00:21:55.892 --> 00:21:56.475
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:21:56.475 --> 00:22:01.640
George, I think if you consider
the interfaces left to right,

00:22:01.640 --> 00:22:03.540
the geometric works out.

00:22:03.540 --> 00:22:11.090
And so if we assume any
ray coming like this,

00:22:11.090 --> 00:22:15.470
going from left bottom to
top right, then it will--

00:22:15.470 --> 00:22:19.580
it is going from a higher
index to lower index, which

00:22:19.580 --> 00:22:22.670
means it will tend to increase
its angle with respect

00:22:22.670 --> 00:22:23.240
to normal.

00:22:23.240 --> 00:22:25.400
So it will keep
bending like this.

00:22:25.400 --> 00:22:27.990
And at some point, there will
be total internal reflection,

00:22:27.990 --> 00:22:29.545
and it will bend towards the--

00:22:29.545 --> 00:22:30.110
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's right, yeah.

00:22:30.110 --> 00:22:31.430
Doesn't happen
here, for example.

00:22:31.430 --> 00:22:32.040
If this ray continues--

00:22:32.040 --> 00:22:33.020
AUDIENCE: And then
again, it will--

00:22:33.020 --> 00:22:33.650
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
It will kind of bend.

00:22:33.650 --> 00:22:33.860
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:22:33.860 --> 00:22:35.270
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yeah.

00:22:35.270 --> 00:22:36.380
AUDIENCE: So maybe--

00:22:36.380 --> 00:22:38.833
I mean, that's just another
way of looking at the problem,

00:22:38.833 --> 00:22:40.250
that if you consider
the interface

00:22:40.250 --> 00:22:45.420
to be normal to the change in
the refractive index, then--

00:22:45.420 --> 00:22:45.957
yeah.

00:22:45.957 --> 00:22:46.790
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:22:46.790 --> 00:22:48.582
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Actually, that's true.

00:22:48.582 --> 00:22:51.080
Snell's Law also
justifies this attraction.

00:22:51.080 --> 00:22:55.190
I mean, the point that
is really hard to swallow

00:22:55.190 --> 00:22:59.270
is why this ray starts bending
inwards at this interface.

00:22:59.270 --> 00:23:01.760
After it has started,
then it has to fall,

00:23:01.760 --> 00:23:04.850
because Snell says
that it should fall.

00:23:04.850 --> 00:23:07.210
So that is consistent.

00:23:07.210 --> 00:23:08.560
So really, this acts--

00:23:08.560 --> 00:23:11.440
you can think of a
mechanical analogy, which

00:23:11.440 --> 00:23:14.230
would be like imagine
that you take a tube

00:23:14.230 --> 00:23:15.360
and you cut it in half.

00:23:15.360 --> 00:23:18.700
So now you have
these hollow sphere.

00:23:18.700 --> 00:23:22.540
And then you launch a billiard
ball into that surface.

00:23:22.540 --> 00:23:25.480
What will the billiard ball do?

00:23:25.480 --> 00:23:26.680
It will spin.

00:23:26.680 --> 00:23:30.070
It will go down, and then up
again, and then down again,

00:23:30.070 --> 00:23:31.870
and spin, and spin, and spin.

00:23:31.870 --> 00:23:35.710
So basically, the
surface in this sort

00:23:35.710 --> 00:23:39.760
of mechanical analogy, the
equivalent of the surface shape

00:23:39.760 --> 00:23:41.605
is the index of refraction here.

00:23:41.605 --> 00:23:44.230
And of course, the billiard ball
is subject to its own gravity.

00:23:44.230 --> 00:23:47.080
And the surface--
how do you call it,

00:23:47.080 --> 00:23:49.840
the [INAUDIBLE] contact
from the surface,

00:23:49.840 --> 00:23:50.990
and so on, and so forth.

00:23:50.990 --> 00:23:57.550
But the bottom line is that
this is a mechanical analog.

00:23:57.550 --> 00:23:58.930
I'm sorry, this is--

00:23:58.930 --> 00:24:01.690
whatever, the mechanical
analogy for this

00:24:01.690 --> 00:24:03.885
is gravity, attraction.

00:24:07.861 --> 00:24:12.153
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:12.153 --> 00:24:13.570
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Yes, provided

00:24:13.570 --> 00:24:16.852
you define the gravitational
potential appropriately

00:24:16.852 --> 00:24:18.310
in terms of the
initial refraction.

00:24:18.310 --> 00:24:20.395
And this will actually come up
near the end of the Hamiltonian

00:24:20.395 --> 00:24:21.280
lecture.

00:24:21.280 --> 00:24:23.750
So I will show you
exactly the formula.

00:24:23.750 --> 00:24:26.350
Did everybody hear his question?

00:24:26.350 --> 00:24:27.345
AUDIENCE: No.

00:24:27.345 --> 00:24:29.220
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
OK, could you repeat it?

00:24:29.220 --> 00:24:31.510
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I was
asking, is the analogy

00:24:31.510 --> 00:24:35.000
between the gravitational force
and the reflective [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:35.500
complete?

00:24:37.567 --> 00:24:39.650
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yeah,
and you have an answer.

00:24:39.650 --> 00:24:44.920
OK, now that I have a
marker, let me also answer--

00:24:44.920 --> 00:24:50.070
so in this case, what I did
is on the left-hand side,

00:24:50.070 --> 00:24:54.370
we have the familiar
quadratic index profile.

00:24:56.890 --> 00:25:02.130
So this is n0 minus the some
coefficient times x squared.

00:25:02.130 --> 00:25:06.520
On the right-hand
side, what I did is

00:25:06.520 --> 00:25:09.460
I chose an index that
[INAUDIBLE] like this.

00:25:13.440 --> 00:25:15.480
I'm exaggerating,
but basically, it

00:25:15.480 --> 00:25:17.550
is still a parabola on
the left and the right,

00:25:17.550 --> 00:25:20.280
but has a different curvature
on the left and the right.

00:25:20.280 --> 00:25:22.847
And the point here is
that the central ray still

00:25:22.847 --> 00:25:23.430
goes straight.

00:25:23.430 --> 00:25:25.320
Of course, this is
a terrible lens.

00:25:25.320 --> 00:25:26.900
It does something
really horrible

00:25:26.900 --> 00:25:28.472
back here, does
not focus properly,

00:25:28.472 --> 00:25:29.430
and so on and so forth.

00:25:29.430 --> 00:25:35.670
But the only reason I did this
is to show that the ray here

00:25:35.670 --> 00:25:38.370
goes straight not because
the index of refraction

00:25:38.370 --> 00:25:43.300
is symmetrical, even though
Colin's point is well taken.

00:25:43.300 --> 00:25:45.550
I mean, the reason it
goes straight here--

00:25:45.550 --> 00:25:48.070
again, you can think of it
in terms of Snell's Law.

00:25:48.070 --> 00:25:50.350
It does not want to go
this way, because it

00:25:50.350 --> 00:25:58.880
would bend to a longer optical
path then the ray next to it.

00:25:58.880 --> 00:26:02.320
It does not want to go
down, because again, it

00:26:02.320 --> 00:26:05.320
would end up with a longer
optical path with respect

00:26:05.320 --> 00:26:06.820
to the ray below it.

00:26:06.820 --> 00:26:09.810
So therefore, it
has to go straight.

00:26:09.810 --> 00:26:12.360
Can you imagine a situation--

00:26:12.360 --> 00:26:13.380
is it always straight?

00:26:13.380 --> 00:26:16.620
Can I actually bend this ray?

00:26:16.620 --> 00:26:19.140
What would I have to do to
make the central ray bend?

00:26:23.680 --> 00:26:25.180
Actually, Colin
answered it already.

00:26:30.730 --> 00:26:32.440
Yeah, they cannot see you.

00:26:32.440 --> 00:26:34.010
Can you--

00:26:34.010 --> 00:26:36.287
AUDIENCE: Curve
the whole profile.

00:26:36.287 --> 00:26:38.620
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: So you
have to put a gradient along

00:26:38.620 --> 00:26:40.480
z in the index of refraction.

00:26:40.480 --> 00:26:44.650
Then if the ray sees a tilted
interface, which basically

00:26:44.650 --> 00:26:48.100
means a gradient of the index of
refraction here, it will bend.

00:26:48.100 --> 00:26:52.380
Because again, Snell
tells it to bend.

00:26:52.380 --> 00:26:53.660
But since there is no--

00:26:53.660 --> 00:26:57.350
since here, the index
has no z dependency,

00:26:57.350 --> 00:26:58.700
then the ray must go straight.

