00:33:01.660 --> 00:33:03.870
So the energy consists,
of course, of two terms.

00:33:03.870 --> 00:33:08.310
One of them is, if you
wish, the elastic energy,

00:33:08.310 --> 00:33:13.890
the potential that is due to the
restoring force of the spring.

00:33:13.890 --> 00:33:15.450
And the other is
the kinetic energy.

00:33:18.030 --> 00:33:24.230
And v is the velocity,
so v is basically x dot,

00:33:24.230 --> 00:33:26.925
the first time derivative
of the position.

00:33:29.700 --> 00:33:31.810
So this is one
thing that we know.

00:33:31.810 --> 00:33:33.270
This is the energy
of the system.

00:33:33.270 --> 00:33:36.420
And since in our model,
there is no dissipation,

00:33:36.420 --> 00:33:39.630
the energy must be conserved.

00:33:39.630 --> 00:33:43.770
I can also write an equation
of motion for this system.

00:33:43.770 --> 00:33:48.000
And since it is a simple
spring force kind of system,

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:51.810
I expect my equation of
motion to be second order,

00:33:51.810 --> 00:33:53.700
so there would be
something of this sort--

00:33:53.700 --> 00:33:59.880
m x double dot plus kx equals
the force, the excitation.

00:34:02.390 --> 00:34:05.710
So let's say that
this system is free.

00:34:05.710 --> 00:34:07.100
There is no force.

00:34:07.100 --> 00:34:12.620
So if it is moving, it is moving
because of a prior excitation,

00:34:12.620 --> 00:34:14.659
which if I start
it [INAUDIBLE] it

00:34:14.659 --> 00:34:17.230
will go on forever, because
there is no dissipation.

00:34:17.230 --> 00:34:18.913
There is no place
for the energy to go.

00:34:18.913 --> 00:34:21.080
If you get this thing moving,
it will go on forever.

00:34:21.080 --> 00:34:22.730
But now, there's no force.

00:34:22.730 --> 00:34:25.310
So basically, I can write
down the equation of motion

00:34:25.310 --> 00:34:29.068
like this, as a
homogeneous equation.

00:34:29.068 --> 00:34:30.860
So there's is a trick
that those of you who

00:34:30.860 --> 00:34:34.630
use Matlab to solve differential
equations are very familiar.

00:34:34.630 --> 00:34:36.350
And the trick is the following--

00:34:36.350 --> 00:34:39.830
you break this higher order
differential equation.

00:34:39.830 --> 00:34:44.449
You break it down into as
many as you need first order

00:34:44.449 --> 00:34:46.010
differential equations.

00:34:46.010 --> 00:34:48.679
Since this is a
second order equation,

00:34:48.679 --> 00:34:51.602
you only need two
first order equations.

00:34:51.602 --> 00:34:53.060
And the way you do
it is basically,

00:34:53.060 --> 00:34:55.550
you write down an equation
that looks kind of stupid.

00:34:55.550 --> 00:35:03.890
The equation says that x dot
equals v. This is one equation.

00:35:03.890 --> 00:35:07.100
And then the other equation
comes from this one--

00:35:07.100 --> 00:35:11.270
since x dot equals v, it means
that x double dot equals v dot.

00:35:11.270 --> 00:35:13.708
This is the acceleration.

00:35:13.708 --> 00:35:15.500
So the second equation
now comes from this,

00:35:15.500 --> 00:35:25.230
that is, v dot equals minus
whatever k over m times x.

00:35:25.230 --> 00:35:34.500
Now, I can define the
vector x v. And what

00:35:34.500 --> 00:35:37.400
this set of equations
here has done,

00:35:37.400 --> 00:35:41.330
it has actually connected the
first derivative of this vector

00:35:41.330 --> 00:35:44.040
with the vector
itself via matrix.

00:35:44.040 --> 00:35:46.730
And here is the vector
in its first derivative.

00:35:46.730 --> 00:35:50.610
Here is the vector itself.

00:35:50.610 --> 00:35:54.230
And what I have to put here in
order to make this look correct

00:35:54.230 --> 00:35:56.180
is I have to put
1 here, and then

00:35:56.180 --> 00:36:02.130
minus k over m here, and
then 0s, and then I'm done.

00:36:02.130 --> 00:36:04.970
So again, if you
ever used Matlab

00:36:04.970 --> 00:36:07.790
to solve an ordinary
differential equation,

00:36:07.790 --> 00:36:08.990
you're familiar with this.

00:36:08.990 --> 00:36:12.800
Matlab actually forces you to
rewrite your equation this way.

00:36:12.800 --> 00:36:14.720
But it turns out that
this kind of method

00:36:14.720 --> 00:36:18.740
actually preceded Matlab
by about a century,

00:36:18.740 --> 00:36:23.270
because this is a standard way
of writing the equation in--

00:36:23.270 --> 00:36:25.820
actually, I believe it was
Poincare who actually first

00:36:25.820 --> 00:36:26.620
came up with this.

00:36:26.620 --> 00:36:33.540
It's the standard way to derive
the dynamics of a system.

00:36:33.540 --> 00:36:37.280
And this is not--

00:36:37.280 --> 00:36:39.290
I don't want to spend
too much time with this.

00:36:39.290 --> 00:36:42.980
But what this slide basically
points out to you is

00:36:42.980 --> 00:36:48.120
the following-- that if you
take this expression here,

00:36:48.120 --> 00:36:51.648
which I will call the energy,
but now we'll call it--

00:36:51.648 --> 00:36:53.690
of course, you cannot see
